<article class="article-body">

<p>An operations manager makes your <em>delivery machine</em> reliable. Here's how to tell you've hit the point where the lack of one is costing you customers and sanity.</p>

<h2>The symptoms</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Response times drift and nobody notices for weeks</strong> — there's no SLA tracking, so quality erodes silently.</li>
  <li><strong>Onboarding lives in one veteran's head</strong> — when they're out, things break; new hires take forever to get productive.</li>
  <li><strong>You can't answer "what's our throughput / SLA compliance?"</strong> without a manual archaeology dig.</li>
  <li><strong>Growth keeps breaking processes</strong> — every new customer or hire creates a fire because the system wasn't built to scale.</li>
  <li><strong>Commitments live in DMs</strong> — no single source of truth for who owes what by when.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What the role actually fixes</h2>
<p>An operations manager installs the systems that make the above disappear: SLA tracking, CRM hygiene and dashboards, documented SOPs, QA frameworks, onboarding playbooks, and the weekly reporting rhythm that keeps it all alive. The output is measurable — response times drop, handoffs stop failing, leadership sees status without asking. (Scope: <a href="/operations-manager-kenya/">remote operations manager</a>.)</p>

<h2>Full-time, fractional, or project?</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Project</strong> — if you need one defined system built (an SLA framework, a CRM dashboard, an onboarding playbook), hire for that, not a headcount.</li>
  <li><strong>Fractional</strong> — if you need someone running the operating rhythm 10–25 hours a week, a <a href="/operations-partner/">fractional operations partner</a> fits.</li>
  <li><strong>Full-time</strong> — once operations is a daily, full-surface job (usually 25+ person delivery teams).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Not sure it's an ops manager you need?</h2>
<p>If the pain is the founder's time, that's an <a href="/executive-assistant-kenya/">executive assistant</a>; if it's strategy stalling, that's a <a href="/chief-of-staff-kenya/">chief of staff</a>. The three are compared in <a href="/blog/executive-assistant-vs-chief-of-staff-vs-operations-manager/">this guide</a>.</p>

<p>Bring your messiest operational pain point to a <a href="/booking/">free 30-minute call</a> and you'll leave with a diagnosis and a 30-day plan.</p>

